
  <sn><md>### Soil Colloids

The **physical chemistry** of soils is essentially a `study of the most reactive fractions of soils`, or the so-called `colloidal phase`. The colloidal particles play an important role in determining the `physical` and `physico-chemical properties` and `reactions` that occur in soils.

---

&gt; A **colloid** is a very tiny particle, usually `smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter`.

`Nutrients are adsorbed on soil colloidal particles`. Hence, the constituents of soil which are in the colloidal state are the **seats of reactions in soil**.

---

#### Clay and Colloidal Materials{.text-center}

`Clays` are important colloidal materials.<br>

The term **‚Äòclay fraction‚Äô** should not be confused with the term **‚Äòclay minerals‚Äô**:
* The **clay fraction** may contain `clay-sized particles` which are not clay minerals.
* Similarly, **clay minerals** may occur in particles that are too large to be included in the clay fraction.

